#reply#In article 29910@rtsg.mot.com, svoboda@rtsg.mot.com (David Svoboda) writes:
#reply#>
#reply#>Well, as many a bored bike tourer can tell you, the way to steer
#reply#>sans hans is to push your body off to the side you want to lean.

Also known as, "leaning."

#reply#>Say you want to turn left....
#reply#[severely confused rambling about the ground pushing...] 
#reply#>but the front wheel has trail.  If the ground pushes the front wheel 
#reply#>toward the left at the contact patch, the trail will cause the 
#reply#>wheel to turn to the right.  Hey, there we are.  No-hands counter-
#reply#>steering.

Contersteering refers to pushing the inside handlebar to effect a
lean.  No-hands countersteering is an oxymoron.

